Supervised Learning - Foundations Project: ReCell¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Buying and selling used phones and tablets used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished device market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth \$52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used phones and tablets that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing one. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used device market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished devices. Maximizing the longevity of devices through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost this segment as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones and tablets only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished devices. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone/tablet and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used/refurbished phones and tablets. The data was collected in the year 2021. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the device runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the device battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the device in grams
  • release_year: Year when the device model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished device has been used
  • normalized_new_price: Normalized price of a new device of the same model in euros
  • normalized_used_price: Normalized price of the used/refurbished device in euros

Functions to plot charts¶

In this section, several functions have been meticulously defined to streamline the process of Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA). Each function is tailored to visualize and analyze different aspects of the dataset. Here's a concise documentation of each function:

plot_numerical(dataframe):

  • Purpose: Facilitates Univariate analysis.
  • Description: Automatically identifies numerical variables in the provided dataframe and generates subplots that include a boxplot and a histogram for each numerical variable. These visualizations aid in understanding the distribution and identifying potential outliers.

plot_categorical(dataframe):

  • Purpose: Facilitates Univariate analysis.
  • Description: Identifies categorical variables within the given dataframe and generates subplots with countplots for each categorical variable. This function is essential for visualizing the frequency distribution of categorical data.

plot_box_hist_ind(dataframe, column, title):

  • Purpose: Conducts Univariate analysis on a single variable.
  • Description: Creates a combined visualization consisting of a box plot and a histogram for the specified column in the dataframe. This dual representation provides a comprehensive view of the distribution, central tendency, and variability of the data.

plot_countplot_ind(dataframe, column, title, labeltype):

  • Purpose: Facilitates Univariate analysis.
  • Description: Generates a countplot for the specified variable, with the option to display data labels as values, percentages, or both. This function is instrumental in visualizing the count of occurrences of each category in a variable.

plot_box_bar(dataframe, x_var, y_var, chart_title):

  • Purpose: Aids in Bivariate analysis.
  • Description: Constructs a boxplot and a barplot side by side for two specified variables, allowing for a detailed comparison and relationship assessment between the variables. This function is particularly useful for comparing the central tendency and dispersion between groups.

plot_single_variable_correlation(correlation_series):

  • Purpose: Identifies correlations for a target variable.
  • Description: Takes a series of correlation values as input and generates a bar chart, showcasing the relationship between the target variable and other numerical variables in the dataset. This visualization is critical for understanding how different variables interact with the target variable.

Each function is designed to extract meaningful insights from the dataset, providing a clear and intuitive understanding of the underlying patterns, trends, and relationships.

def plot_numerical(dataframe):
    # Extract numerical variables
    numeric_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns
    num_vars = len(numeric_columns)

    # Calculate the number of rows for the subplot
    num_rows = (num_vars // 3) + (1 if num_vars % 3 != 0 else 0)

    # Set up the matplotlib figure
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2 * num_rows, 3, figsize=(20, 5 * num_rows * 1.25), constrained_layout=True, gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [1, 4] * num_rows})

    # Loop through the numerical variables to create boxplots and histograms
    for i, column in enumerate(numeric_columns):
        # Define the row and column index in the subplot grid
        row = (i // 3) * 2
        col = i % 3

        # Create a boxplot for the variable
        sns.boxplot(data=dataframe, x=column, ax=axes[row, col])
        axes[row, col].set_title(f'Box Plot and Histogram for {column}', fontsize=12)
        axes[row, col].tick_params(labelbottom=False)  # Remove x-ticks for the boxplot
        axes[row, col].set_xlabel('')  # Remove x-axis label for the boxplot

        # Create a histogram for the variable
        sns.histplot(data=dataframe, x=column, kde=True, ax=axes[row + 1, col], binwidth=None)
        axes[row + 1, col].set_title('')  # Remove title for the histogram
        axes[row + 1, col].set_xlabel(f'{column}\n\n')  # Set x-axis label for the histogram

    # Remove the excess axes
    i += 1
    delrow =  (i // 3) * 2
    delcol = i % 3
    fig.delaxes(axes[delrow, delcol])
    fig.delaxes(axes[delrow + 1, delcol])

    plt.show()

def plot_categorical(dataframe):
    # Extract categorical variables
    categorical_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns
    num_vars = len(categorical_columns) - 1  # Excluding 'brand_name'

    # Calculate the number of rows for the FacetGrid-like layout
    num_rows = 1 + (num_vars // 3 + (1 if num_vars % 3 != 0 else 0))

    # Set up the matplotlib figure
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, 3, figsize=(20, 5 * num_rows), constrained_layout=True)

    # Flatten the axes array for easy iteration if there are multiple rows
    if axes.ndim > 1:
        axes = axes.flatten()

    # Calculate the counts and sort for 'brand_name'
    order_brand_name = dataframe['brand_name'].value_counts().index
    total_brand_name = len(dataframe['brand_name'])

    # Create a new big subplot for 'brand_name' that spans the first row
    big_ax_brand_name = fig.add_subplot(num_rows, 1, 1)
    brand_name_plot = sns.countplot(x='brand_name', data=dataframe, ax=big_ax_brand_name, order=order_brand_name)
    big_ax_brand_name.set_title('Count of brand_name', fontsize=12)
    big_ax_brand_name.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
    big_ax_brand_name.set_xlabel('')

    # Add data labels for 'brand_name'
    for p in brand_name_plot.patches:
        count = p.get_height()
        percentage = 100 * count / total_brand_name
        axx = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
        axy = p.get_height()
        big_ax_brand_name.annotate(f'{int(count)} ({percentage:.1f}%)', (axx, axy), ha='center', va='bottom', rotation=90)

    # Hide the original axes in the first row
    for ax in axes[:3]:
        ax.remove()

    # Loop through the remaining categorical variables to create count plots
    for i, column in enumerate(categorical_columns[1:], start=1):
        # Define the row and column index in the subplot grid
        row = (i - 1) // 3 + 1  # +1 because the first entire row is for 'brand_name'
        col = (i - 1) % 3
        total = len(dataframe[column])

        # Create countplot
        ax = axes[row * 3 + col]
        plot = sns.countplot(x=column, data=dataframe, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f'Count of {column}', fontsize=12)
        ax.tick_params(axis='x')

        # Add data labels
        for p in plot.patches:
            count = p.get_height()
            percentage = 100 * count / total
            axx = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
            axy = p.get_height()
            ax.annotate(f'{int(count)} ({percentage:.1f}%)', (axx, axy), ha='center', va='bottom')

    # Adjust layout
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def plot_box_hist_ind(dataframe, column, title):
    """
    Plot a box plot and a histogram for the specified column of the dataframe.

    :param dataframe: pandas DataFrame
    :param column: string, the name of the column to plot
    :param title: string, the title for the plots
    """
    # Set up a grid layout with 2 rows
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 6), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [1, 4]})

    # Plotting the boxplot on the first row
    sns.boxplot(x=dataframe[column], ax=ax[0], color='lightblue')
    ax[0].set_title(f'Box Plot and Histogram for {title}')
    ax[0].tick_params(labelbottom=False)  # Remove x-ticks for the boxplot
    ax[0].set_xlabel('')  # Hide x-axis label for the boxplot

    # Plotting the histogram on the second row
    sns.histplot(dataframe[column], kde=True, color='skyblue', ax=ax[1])

    # Calculate the mean and median
    mean_price = dataframe[column].mean()
    median_price = dataframe[column].median()
    min_price = dataframe[column].min()
    max_price = dataframe[column].max()

    # Add vertical lines for mean, median, min, and max
    ax[1].axvline(mean_price, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=1, label=f'Mean: {mean_price:.2f}')
    ax[1].axvline(median_price, color='green', linestyle='-', linewidth=1, label=f'Median: {median_price:.2f}')
    ax[1].axvline(min_price, color='blue', linestyle=':', linewidth=1, label=f'Min: {min_price:.2f}')
    ax[1].axvline(max_price, color='purple', linestyle='-.', linewidth=1, label=f'Max: {max_price:.2f}')

    # Add title and labels for clarity in the histogram
    ax[1].set_title('')  # Hide title for the histogram
    ax[1].set_xlabel(title, fontsize=12)
    ax[1].set_ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=12)

    # Display legends
    ax[1].legend()

    # Adjust layout
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Display the plot
    plt.show()

def plot_countplot_ind(dataframe, column, title, labeltype):
    """
    Plot a countplot for a specified column in the dataframe with value, percentage, value (percentage), or
    value (% to overall count for the brand in uddf) labels.

    Args:
    dataframe (pd.DataFrame): The dataframe containing the data (subset or specific view).
    column (str): The name of the column for which to create the countplot.
    title (str): The title of the plot.
    labeltype (str): Type of label to display ('value', 'percentage', 'valperc', or 'valueoverallperc').
      labeltype = 'value' > Prints count for the variable
      labeltype = 'percentage' > Prints percentage (proportion) of the count
      labeltype = 'valperc' > Prints count as well as percentage of the count
      labeltype = 'valueoverallperc' > Prints count of the filtered dataframe and percentage to count of the original dataframe
    uddf (pd.DataFrame, optional): The original dataframe for comparison if labeltype is 'valueoverallperc'.
    """
    # Set up the figure size
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 8))

    # Calculate the counts and sort for the column based on the provided dataframe
    order = dataframe[column].value_counts().index

    # Create a countplot for the specified column
    ax = sns.countplot(data=dataframe, x=column, order=order, color='skyblue')

    # Add title and labels for clarity
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel('Count')

    # Define total_devices outside of the loop for efficiency
    total_devices = len(dataframe)

    # Calculate the total number of devices for each category in the overall dataframe if labeltype is 'valueoverallperc'
    if labeltype == 'valueoverallperc':
        overall_totals = uddf[column].value_counts()

    # Add data labels
    for i, p in enumerate(ax.patches):
        height = p.get_height()  # get the height of each bar
        axx = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
        axy = height
        if labeltype == 'value':
            label = f'{int(height)}'
        elif labeltype == 'percentage':
            percentage = 100 * height / total_devices
            label = f'{percentage:.1f}%'
        elif labeltype == 'valperc':
            percentage = 100 * height / total_devices
            label = f'{int(height)} ({percentage:.1f}%)'
        elif labeltype == 'valueoverallperc':
            brand_name = order[i]  # Get the brand name from the order list
            overall_percentage = 100 * height / overall_totals[brand_name]
            label = f'{int(height)} ({overall_percentage:.1f}%)'
        ax.annotate(label, (axx, axy), ha='center', va='bottom', rotation=90)

    # Rotate x-labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()


def plot_box_bar(dataframe, x_var, y_var, chart_title):
    """
    Plot a boxplot and a barplot as subplots to show the distribution and mean of a numerical variable across different categories.

    Args:
    dataframe (pd.DataFrame): The dataframe containing the data.
    x_var (str): The name of the numerical variable.
    y_var (str): The name of the categorical variable.
    chart_title (str): The title of the charts.

    """
    # Set up the figure size and subplots layout
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(20, 10), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [1, 1]})

    # Create a boxplot on the first row
    sns.boxplot(data=dataframe, x=x_var, y=y_var, palette='Blues', ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title(f'Boxplot and Barplot of {chart_title}')
    axes[0].set_xlabel('')  # Hide x-axis label
    axes[0].tick_params(labelbottom=False)  # Remove x-ticks for the boxplot
    axes[0].set_ylabel(y_var)

    # Create a barplot on the second row
    sns.barplot(data=dataframe, x=x_var, y=y_var, palette='Blues', ax=axes[1])
    axes[1].set_title('')  # Hide title
    axes[1].set_xlabel(x_var)
    axes[1].set_ylabel(f'Mean {x_var}')

    # Rotate x-labels for better readability if necessary
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # Adjust layout
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

def plot_single_variable_correlation(correlation_series):
    """
    Plot a vertical bar chart based on the given correlation series using Seaborn, including data labels on the bars.

    Args:
    correlation_series (pd.Series): A series representing the correlation values of a single variable with others.
    """
    # Set the figure size
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

    # Create a vertical bar chart using Seaborn
    ax = sns.barplot(x=correlation_series.index, y=correlation_series.values, palette="Blues")

    # Add title and labels for clarity
    plt.title('Correlation with Normalized Used Price')
    plt.xlabel('Variables')
    plt.ylabel('Correlation Value')

    # Add data labels
    for p in ax.patches:
        width = p.get_width()
        height = p.get_height()
        plt.text(p.get_x() + width / 2,  # x-coordinate position of data label, to align with the middle of the bar
                 height + 0.01,  # y-coordinate position of data label, padded 0.01 above the bar
                 f'{height:.2f}',  # data label, formatted to 2 decimal places
                 ha='center',  # center alignment
                 va='bottom')  # bottom alignment

    # Rotate x-labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

Questions and Answers¶

1. What does the distribution of normalized used device prices look like?¶

Ans: The distribution of normalized used device prices predominantly exhibits a normal pattern. However, there are noticeable outliers present at both the lower and upper extremes of the distribution as captured under boxplot.

2. What percentage of the used device market is dominated by Android devices?¶

Ans: Android holds a commanding presence in the used device market, encompassing 93.1% (3214 devices) of the total. This substantial market share may reflect a widespread consumer preference or a broader availability of Android-based devices, underlining its dominance in the sector.

3. The amount of RAM is important for the smooth functioning of a device. How does the amount of RAM vary with the brand?¶

Ans: RAM allocation varies significantly across brands, with each brand exhibiting a unique distribution pattern as evident from the box plots.

  • The RAM distributions for brands are not normally distributed, implying a varied range of RAM offerings within each brand.
  • Each brand's RAM distribution includes outliers, indicating exceptional cases of extremely low or high RAM capacities within brands.
  • Among the diversity, it stands out that 81.5% of devices (2815 of 3454) use 4 GB RAM and all brands (34) manufactures devices with 4GB RAM.
  • OnePlus stands out for offering devices with the highest RAM, while Celkon is noted for having devices with the least RAM.

Outlier Treatments¶

Treating outliers is essential in preparing the data for Linear Regression, as extreme values can disproportionately affect the model's performance. Following function is written to visualize the outliers;

  1. plot_numeric_boxplot(dataframe): This function will plot boxplots for all numeric variables to visualize the data and to understand the distribution and identify potential outliers.
In [24]:
def plot_numeric_boxplots(dataframe):
    """
    Plot boxplots for all numeric variables in the dataframe, displaying 4 boxplots per row.

    Args:
    dataframe (pd.DataFrame): The dataframe containing the data.
    """
    num_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns
    num_of_columns = len(num_columns)
    num_of_rows = (num_of_columns - 1) // 4 + 1  # Calculate the number of rows needed

    # Set up the matplotlib figure
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_of_rows, 4, figsize=(20, 5 * num_of_rows))

    for i, column in enumerate(num_columns):
        # Determine the position of the current plot
        row = i // 4
        col = i % 4

        if num_of_rows == 1:  # If there's only one row, axes is a 1D array
            ax = axes[col]
        else:  # Otherwise, axes is a 2D array
            ax = axes[row, col]

        sns.boxplot(x=dataframe[column], ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f'Boxplot of {column}', fontsize=14)

        # If there are no more columns to plot, hide the remaining axes
        if i == num_of_columns - 1:
            for j in range(i + 1, num_of_rows * 4):
                axes.flat[j].set_visible(False)

    # Adjust layout
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def remove_outliers(dataframe):
    """
    Remove outliers for all numeric variables in the dataframe based on the IQR method, except for 'ram'.

    Args:
    dataframe (pd.DataFrame): The dataframe containing the data.

    Returns:
    pd.DataFrame: The dataframe with outliers removed, except for 'ram'.
    """
    Q1 = dataframe.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = dataframe.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1

    # Define numeric columns, excluding 'ram'
    numeric_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns
    numeric_columns = numeric_columns.drop('ram') if 'ram' in numeric_columns else numeric_columns

    # Cap the outliers
    for column in numeric_columns:
        lower_bound = Q1[column] - 1.5 * IQR[column]
        upper_bound = Q3[column] + 1.5 * IQR[column]
        dataframe[column] = dataframe[column].clip(lower=lower_bound, upper=upper_bound)

    return dataframe

Feature Engineering¶

Dropping column brand_name¶

Rationale behind dropping brand_name:

High Dimensionality: One-hot encoding the brand_name with 34 unique categories would significantly increase the dataset's dimensionality, leading to potential overfitting.

Redundancy with os: The os column, which has fewer categories, may capture relevant brand-related information, making brand_name potentially redundant.

Model Simplification: Removing brand_name simplifies the model, aiding interpretability and reducing the risk of multicollinearity, especially when combined with other categorical variables like os.

Model Performance Check¶

Evaluating model performance is essential to confirm its accuracy, reliability, and generalization to new data. It identifies strengths and areas for improvement, ensuring the model's real-world applicability.

Evaluating Model Performance: A comprehensive set of metrics including RMSE, MAE, R-squared, Adjusted R-squared, and MAPE will be used to assess the model's predictive accuracy and explanatory power. These metrics, presented in a unified dataframe, offer a detailed evaluation, guiding model refinement and optimization.

Functions to check the performance of the model using different metrics.¶

In [37]:
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    """
    Calculate adjusted R-squared score.

    Args:
    predictors: numpy array or pandas dataframe containing predictor variables
    targets: numpy array or pandas series containing actual target values
    predictions: numpy array or pandas series containing predicted values

    Returns:
    float: adjusted R-squared score
    """
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]  # number of observations
    k = predictors.shape[1]  # number of predictor variables
    # Adjusted R-squared calculation
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    """
    Calculate Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE).

    Args:
    targets: numpy array or pandas series containing actual target values
    predictions: numpy array or pandas series containing predicted values

    Returns:
    float: MAPE score
    """
    # MAPE calculation
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Compute performance metrics for a regression model.

    Args:
    model: trained regression model
    predictors: numpy array or pandas dataframe containing predictor variables
    target: numpy array or pandas series containing actual target values

    Returns:
    pd.DataFrame: dataframe containing performance metrics
    """
    # Making predictions using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Calculating various performance metrics
    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # Compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # Compute Adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # Compute Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # Compute Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # Compute Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)

    # Creating a dataframe to display the metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.
  1. Test for Multicollinearity
  2. Treating High P-value
  3. Test for Linearity and Independence
  4. Test for Normality
  5. Test for Homoscedasticity

1. Test for Multicollinearity¶

  • Multicollinearity testing ensures predictor variables in the regression model are independent.
  • The Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) will be used to identify and quantify multicollinearity among predictors.
In [40]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

def checking_vif(predictors):
    """
    Calculates the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) for each predictor variable to identify multicollinearity issues in the regression model.
    Args: predictors (DataFrame): DataFrame containing the predictor variables.
    Returns: DataFrame: DataFrame with features and their corresponding VIF.
    """
    # Initialize a DataFrame to store VIF values
    vif = pd.DataFrame()

    # Add the feature names to the DataFrame
    vif["feature"] = predictors.columns

    # Calculate VIF for each feature and store it in the DataFrame
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(predictors.values, i)
        for i in range(len(predictors.columns))
    ]

    # Return the DataFrame containing features and their VIF values
    return vif

Multicollinearity Mitigation Steps¶

Affected columns: screen_size and weight.

Define function to complete the following tasks:

  1. Iterative Removal: Sequentially drop columns with VIF > 5, one at a time.
  2. Model Evaluation: Post-removal, assess the model using Adjusted R-squared and RMSE.
  3. Minimal Impact Selection: Prefer dropping the column with the least effect on Adjusted R-squared.
  4. VIF Recalculation: Reevaluate VIF scores after each column removal.
  5. Completion Check: Continue the process until all VIF scores are below 5.
In [42]:
# Function to drop affected column and test the model performance after dropping.

def treating_multicollinearity(predictors, target, high_vif_columns):
    """
    Evaluate the impact of removing high VIF columns on model performance (Adj. R-squared & RMSE).

    Args:
    predictors (pd.DataFrame): DataFrame containing predictor variables.
    target (pd.Series): Series containing target variable.
    high_vif_columns (list): List of column names with high VIF.

    Returns:
    pd.DataFrame: DataFrame with performance metrics after dropping each high VIF column.
    """
    adj_r2 = []  # Store adjusted R-squared values
    rmse = []    # Store RMSE values

    # Iterate through high VIF columns and assess model performance after dropping each
    for col in high_vif_columns:
        # Define the predictor set excluding the current high VIF column
        train = predictors.drop(columns=[col])

        # Fit OLS model
        ols_model = sm.OLS(target, train).fit()

        # Append performance metrics
        adj_r2.append(ols_model.rsquared_adj)
        rmse.append(np.sqrt(ols_model.mse_resid))

    # Compile results into a DataFrame
    result_df = pd.DataFrame({
        "Dropped Column": high_vif_columns,
        "Adj. R-squared": adj_r2,
        "RMSE": rmse,
    }).sort_values(by="Adj. R-squared", ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

    return result_df

2. Treating High P-value¶

In the regression model:

Null Hypothesis ($H_0$): The predictor has no impact on normalized_used_price (coefficient = 0).

Alternative Hypothesis ($H_1$): The predictor significantly affects normalized_used_price (coefficient ≠ 0).

A p-value < 0.05 rejects H0, indicating a significant relationship. A higher p-value suggests no significant impact.

In this section, we will identify all non-significant predectors and remove one at a time to understand its impact of other predictors.

We'll streamline the process as follows:

  1. Build a model, identify the variable with the highest p-value, and remove it.
  2. Construct a new model without the removed feature and repeat step 1. Continue until all variables have p-values < 0.05.

Note: While this can be done manually, using a loop enhances efficiency and reduces tedium.

In [46]:
# Copy the initial list of predictor columns
predictors = X_train2.copy()
cols = predictors.columns.tolist()

# Initialize the maximum p-value
max_p_value = 1

while len(cols) > 0:
    # Define the training set with the current set of predictors
    X_train_aux = predictors[cols]

    # Fit the OLS model with the current predictors
    model = sm.OLS(y_train, X_train_aux).fit()

    # Retrieve the p-values of the model's predictors
    p_values = model.pvalues
    # Get the maximum p-value among the predictors
    max_p_value = max(p_values)
    # Identify the predictor with the highest p-value
    feature_with_p_max = p_values.idxmax()

    # If the highest p-value is greater than the threshold (0.05), remove the corresponding predictor
    if max_p_value > 0.05:
        cols.remove(feature_with_p_max)
    else:
        # If all p-values are below the threshold, stop the loop
        break

# The final list of predictors after removing those with high p-values
selected_features = cols
print(selected_features)

3. Test for Linearity and Independence¶

Why Test?: We test to ensure a linear relationship between predictors and the dependent variable and to confirm that error terms are independent, safeguarding the accuracy of coefficient estimates.

Checking Method: Plot the residuals against fitted values. The absence of patterns indicates linearity and independent residuals; patterns suggest non-linearity and dependence.

Resolution: If the assumption is violated, consider transforming variables to establish linearity.

4. Test for Normality¶

Purpose: To ensure residuals are normally distributed for reliable coefficient estimates and confidence intervals.

Assessment: Use histograms, Q-Q plots, and Shapiro-Wilk test to examine residual distribution.

Resolution: If normality is violated, consider applying log, exponential, or arcsinh transformations.

5. Test for Homoscedasticity¶

Homoscedasticity ($H_0$): implies that residuals exhibit constant variance across the regression line.

Heteroscedasticity ($H_a$): refers to a situation where residuals' variance is not constant.

Importance of the Test: Heteroscedasticity often arises due to outliers, leading to unreliable standard errors.

Assessment Methods:

  • Residuals versus fitted values plots help detect homoscedasticity; non-random patterns suggest heteroscedasticity.
  • The Goldfeld-Quandt test, where a p-value > 0.05 supports homoscedastic residuals.

Remediation: Address heteroscedasticity by incorporating key variables or applying data transformations.

  • Therefore, we assume that the Homoscedasticity assumption is satisfied and we will continue using the olsmodel3 as our final model.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Insights:¶

  • The final OLS model explains approximately 84% of the variance in used device prices.
  • Model reveals significant positive correlation between normalized new device price with normalized used device price, stating that every unit increase in new_device_price brings 0.4255 unit increase in normalized_used_price.
  • Device's age and number of days used have negatice coefficients which indicates the used device prices drops for older or more used phones.
  • Significant predictors include screen size (0.0433) and 4G capability (0.0365), while main camera MP, selfie camera MP, and RAM influence normalized used device prices moderately.
  • The model's const coefficient (1.2258) suggests a base price level for the used devices.
  • RMSE for the training set is 0.235011 and for the test set is 0.238672, indicating a good fit with low prediction error.
  • MAE for the training set is 0.184164 and for the test set is 0.184313, confirming the model's accuracy in predicting used device prices.
  • MAPE values are 4.42% for the training set and 4.49% for the test set, reflecting the model's capability to predict prices within a narrow error margin.
  • Despite high multicollinearity indicated by the condition number, the model maintains robust predictive power.

Recommendations:¶

  • Prioritize the predictive factors with the highest influence on used device prices, such as new device prices and 4g capability, to refine the pricing model.
  • Continue to assess the impact of multicollinearity on the model and consider dimensionality reduction techniques or non-linear transformations, if necessary.
  • Implement robust standard errors in the model to address any heteroscedasticity concerns.
  • Evaluate the model periodically with new data to ensure its predictive power remains strong over time.
  • Consider the development of a dynamic pricing tool that uses this model to help set competitive prices for used devices.
  • Conduct a sensitivity analysis to understand the impact of each feature on the price prediction.
  • Use the insights from the model to guide inventory purchasing decisions—prioritizing devices with features that drive higher prices.
  • Keep an eye on market trends and be ready to update the model as new device features become significant in determining price.

Observations:¶

Correlation with normalized_used_price:

  • The correlation between normalized_used_price and normalized_new_price is very high (0.83), which is expected as the price of a used device is often influenced by its original new price.

  • screen_size, main_camera_mp, selfie_camera_mp, battery, and ram show moderate positive correlations with normalized_used_price. This indicates that devices with larger screens, higher camera resolutions, more battery capacity, more RAM, and newer release years tend to have higher used prices. These factors are important facrors in predicting used device prices.

Multicollinearity Concerns:

  • screen_size and weight have a very high positive correlation (0.83), suggesting multicollinearity. It's common for larger devices to weigh more, but this relationship might inflate the coefficients in a regression model.

  • screen_size and battery also show a high correlation (0.81) which is likely due to larger phones may demand more power, a potential candidate for multicollinearity.

  • battery and weight shows high correlation (0.70), which is expected as larger batteries may weigh more.

Other Observations:

  • It's also worth noting the negative correlation of days_used with normalized_used_price, indicating that devices used for longer periods tend to decrease in value.

Given these observations, further analysis and model building should carefully consider the potential multicollinearity, especially when including features like screen_size, weight, battery, and days_used.
